      { q: 'Evaluate the view that supply-side policies are more effective than demand-side policies in achieving long-term economic growth.', marks: 8, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(1) Supply-side policies shift LRAS right, increasing potential output without necessarily causing inflation. (1) They address structural issues: education improves productivity, deregulation increases competition and efficiency. (1) They can improve the trade-off between inflation and unemployment by lowering the natural rate. (1) However, they have very long time lags — education and infrastructure take years to yield results. (1) They cannot address short-run demand deficiency during recessions. (1) Free-market supply-side policies may increase inequality (e.g., reducing workers\' rights, cutting top tax rates). (1) Demand-side policies are needed to manage the economic cycle and maintain employment. (1) Conclusion: both are needed — supply-side for long-term capacity, demand-side for short-term stabilisation. Neither alone is sufficient for balanced, sustained growth.' },
      { q: 'Assess whether the Bank of England should abandon its 2% inflation target and instead target nominal GDP growth.', marks: 6, tier: 'red', modelAnswer: '(1) The 2% CPI target provides clarity, transparency, and accountability for monetary policy, anchoring inflation expectations. (1) However, it may be too rigid — it forces tightening even when inflation is driven by temporary supply shocks (e.g., oil prices), potentially causing unnecessary unemployment. (1) NGDP targeting would allow the Bank to tolerate higher inflation during recessions if real growth is weak, providing better automatic stabilisation. (1) Critics argue NGDP is harder to measure in real time and less well understood by the public, potentially weakening expectation anchoring. (1) The current framework has broadly delivered stability since 1997 — changing targets creates transition uncertainty. (1) On balance, the case for change is theoretically attractive but practically risky; marginal reforms (e.g., widening the target band) may be preferable to a complete regime change.' }
