      { q: 'Explain why a firm might experience diseconomies of scale as it grows larger.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(1) Communication problems — as the firm grows, information may be distorted or delayed as it passes through multiple layers of management. (1) Coordination difficulties — managing large numbers of employees, departments, and operations becomes increasingly complex. (1) Worker motivation may fall as employees feel less valued and less connected to the firm\'s objectives in a very large organisation.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the principal-agent problem might lead to satisficing behaviour.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(1) Shareholders (principals) want profit maximisation to maximise their dividends and share value. (1) Managers (agents) have day-to-day control and may pursue their own interests (salary, perks, empire-building). (1) Information asymmetry means shareholders cannot fully monitor whether managers are truly maximising profit. (1) This leads to satisficing — managers achieve an acceptable minimum level of profit to keep shareholders content while pursuing other personal objectives such as growth or a quiet life.' },
      { q: 'Explain two benefits of horizontal integration for a firm.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(1) Increased market share and market power, potentially allowing the firm to influence prices and earn higher profits. (1) This may reduce competition, making demand less elastic and more predictable. (1) Exploitation of economies of scale — combining operations (marketing, purchasing, administration) reduces average costs. (1) Risk reduction through increased size and potential diversification of the customer base.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the short run and long run in economics, using an example.', marks: 3, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: '(1) In the short run, at least one factor of production is fixed — e.g., a restaurant cannot instantly expand its building. (1) In the long run, all factors are variable — the restaurant can move to larger premises, hire more staff, and install new equipment. (1) This distinction matters because in the short run the law of diminishing returns applies, while in the long run the firm can experience economies or diseconomies of scale.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, illustrate how economies and diseconomies of scale affect the long-run average cost curve of a firm.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(1) Draw a U-shaped LRAC curve with output on the x-axis and cost on the y-axis. (1) The downward-sloping section shows economies of scale — as output increases, LRAC falls due to purchasing, technical, and financial economies. (1) The minimum point represents the minimum efficient scale (MES). (1) The upward-sloping section shows diseconomies of scale — LRAC rises due to communication breakdowns, coordination difficulties, and loss of worker motivation as the firm grows too large.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram to show how the short-run average cost curve relates to the long-run average cost curve, and explain the concept of the envelope curve.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', diagram: true, modelAnswer: '(1) Draw multiple U-shaped SRAC curves, each representing a different fixed plant size. (1) The LRAC curve is the envelope of all possible SRAC curves, tangent to each one. (1) Each point on the LRAC represents the lowest cost achievable for that output level when all factors are variable. (1) In the long run, the firm can choose the optimal plant size for any given output, moving along the LRAC rather than being constrained to one SRAC.' }
